# Debug on Dev

**Trigger:** user says "debug on dev" (or clearly means investigate dev environment errors).

## Phase 1 — Inspect pods

Follow **k8s-kubectl-kubeconfig** rule first (`export KUBECONFIG=…` in same shell).

Use namespace **`dev`** (`dev` branch deploys here per `backend/.gitlab-ci.yml`).

```bash
kubectl get pods -n dev
kubectl get pods -n dev -l app=<service-name>
kubectl logs -n dev <pod> -c <container> --tail=200
kubectl logs -n dev <pod> -c <container> --previous   # CrashLoopBackOff
kubectl describe pod -n dev <pod>
```

**Service hints** (deployment names ≈ Helm app names):

| Repo | GitLab | Examples |
|------|--------|----------|
| `backend/` | https://gitlab.mgt/autopilot/re-sharing/backend | `frontend-api`, `location-service`, `provider-adapter-autopilot`, … |
| `fleet/` | https://gitlab.mgt/autopilot/re-sharing/fleet | `fleet-admin-api`, `fleet-catalog`, `fleet-broker-api`, `fleet-ingest-worker` |

Infer repo from changed paths or service prefix (`fleet-*` → fleet).

## Phase 2 — After push to `dev`

Push to `dev` triggers CI automatically. Watch the matching pipeline:

- Backend: https://gitlab.mgt/autopilot/re-sharing/backend/-/pipelines
- Fleet: https://gitlab.mgt/autopilot/re-sharing/fleet/-/pipelines

Check status via GitLab MCP (`pipeline-status`) when available; else from repo dir:

```bash
cd backend   # or fleet
glab ci status
```

Stages: `generate-build-pipeline` → `build` → `deploy` → `rolling-update`. Wait for deploy/rolling-update success before assuming new code is live.

Then re-run Phase 1: confirm pod rollout (`kubectl get pods -n dev`), tail logs for startup/migration/gRPC errors.

## Phase 3 — Report

Summarize: failing CI job (if any), log excerpts with pod/container name, whether issue persists after deploy.
